The provided solution demonstrates how to perform long division in base 5, which is similar to the process in base 10. The key insight is to recognize that the same principles of long division apply, but the values and multiplication tables are based on the specific base system being used.
1. Set up the long division problem in base 5:
   $$
   \begin{array}{c|ccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} &  &  \\
   \cline{2-4}
   2 & 4 & 1 & 3 \\
   \end{array}
   $$

2. Divide the leftmost digit of the dividend ($4_5$) by the divisor ($2_5$). In base 5, $4_5 \div 2_5 = 2_5$. Write the result ($2_5$) above the division line.
   $$
   \begin{array}{c|ccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{2} &  &  \\
   \cline{2-4}
   2 & 4 & 1 & 3 \\
   \end{array}
   $$

3. Multiply the result ($2_5$) by the divisor ($2_5$) and write the product ($4_5$) below the leftmost digit of the dividend.
   $$
   \begin{array}{c|ccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{2} &  &  \\
   \cline{2-4}
   2 & 4 & 1 & 3 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{4} & \downarrow & \\
   \end{array}
   $$

4. Subtract the product ($4_5$) from the leftmost digit of the dividend ($4_5$) and write the difference ($0_5$) below.
   $$
   \begin{array}{c|ccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{2} &  &  \\
   \cline{2-4}
   2 & 4 & 1 & 3 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{4} & \downarrow & \\ \cline{2-2}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{0} & 1 & \\
   \end{array}
   $$

5. Bring down the next digit ($1_5$) from the dividend.
   $$
   \begin{array}{c|ccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{2} & 0 &  \\
   \cline{2-4}
   2 & 4 & 1 & 3 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{4} & \downarrow & \\ \cline{2-2}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{0} & 1 & \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 0 & \downarrow \\
   \end{array}
   $$

6. Divide $13_5$ by $2_5$. In base 5, $13_5 \div 2_5 = 4_5$ (since $4_5 \times 2_5 = 13_5$). Write the result ($4_5$) above the division line.
   $$
   \begin{array}{c|ccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{2} & 0 & 4 \\
   \cline{2-4}
   2 & 4 & 1 & 3 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{4} & \downarrow & \\ \cline{2-2}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{0} & 1 & \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 0 & \downarrow \\ \cline{3-3}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 1 & 3 \\
   \end{array}
   $$

7. Multiply the result ($4_5$) by the divisor ($2_5$) and write the product ($13_5$) below the remaining digits of the dividend.
   $$
   \begin{array}{c|ccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{2} & 0 & 4 \\
   \cline{2-4}
   2 & 4 & 1 & 3 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{4} & \downarrow & \\ \cline{2-2}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{0} & 1 & \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 0 & \downarrow \\ \cline{3-3}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 1 & 3 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 1 & 3 \\
   \end{array}
   $$

8. Subtract the product ($13_5$) from the remaining digits of the dividend ($13_5$). The difference is $0_5$, indicating that the division is complete.
   $$
   \begin{array}{c|ccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{2} & 0 & 4 \\
   \cline{2-4}
   2 & 4 & 1 & 3 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{4} & \downarrow & \\ \cline{2-2}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{0} & 1 & \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 0 & \downarrow \\ \cline{3-3}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 1 & 3 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 1 & 3 \\ \cline{3-4}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & 0
   \end{array}
   $$

The key insight in this problem is that for the remainder to be constant, the coefficient of $x$ in the remainder must be zero. This is because any non-zero coefficient of $x$ would make the remainder dependent on the value of $x$, and thus, not constant. By setting the coefficient of $x$ to zero and solving the resulting equation, we can find the value of $a$ that ensures a constant remainder.
We perform the polynomial division: $$
\begin{array}{c|cc cc}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{5x} & +4 \\
\cline{2-5}
2x^2-3x+1 & 10x^3&-7x^2&+ax&+6   \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{-10x^3} & +15x^2 & -5x \\
\cline{2-4}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{0} & 8x^2 & (a-5)x & 6 \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & -8x^2 & +12x & -4 \\
\cline{3-5}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 0 & (a-5+12)x & 2 \\
\end{array}
$$The remainder will be constant if and only if $a-5+12=0.$ So $a = \boxed{-7}.$

The key insight in this solution is to recognize that the terms in the sum repeat in a pattern modulo 15. By replacing each term with its equivalent modulo 15, we can simplify the sum and find the value of $n$.
1. Observe that the terms in the sum repeat in a pattern modulo 15:
   $$\begin{align*}
   &1+6+11+16+21+26+\cdots+91+96+101\\
   &\qquad\equiv 1+6+11+1+6+11+\cdots+1+6+11 \pmod{15}
   \end{align*}$$

2. Note that the terms $1+6+11$ are repeated 7 times on the right-hand side.

3. Calculate the sum of the repeating terms:
   $$1+6+11=18\equiv 3\pmod{15}$$

4. Rewrite the sum using the repeated terms:
   $$\begin{align*}
   1+6+11&+16+21+26+\cdots+91+96+101\\
   &\equiv \underbrace{1+6+11}_3+\underbrace{1+6+11}_3+\cdots+\underbrace{1+6+11}_3 \pmod{15}
   \end{align*}$$

5. Simplify the sum:
   $$\begin{align*}
   &\equiv 7\cdot 3 \\
   &= 21 \\
   &\equiv 6\pmod{15}
   \end{align*}$$

